Lateinamerika im Kampf gegen das Coronavirus
SÃO PAULO/SANTIAGO/BOGOTÁ/MEXICO CITY – Die COVID-19-Pandemie ist ein Schock von beispielloser Größe und unbekannter Dauer.
Die Folgen sind bereits jetzt katastrophal.
Treten wir der Krise nicht entschieden entgegen, könnte sie zur tragischsten Episode in der lateinamerikanischen Geschichte werden.
Bis jetzt waren die politischen Reaktionen in unserer Region sehr unterschiedlich.
Some governments reacted quickly and declared the protection of public health to be their top priority.
Others, however, unfortunately downplayed the dangers of the pandemic, provided their citizens with false information, and ignored not only scientific research but also the advice of their own experts.
These state leaders opted for a populist and divisive policy in the midst of the tragedy.
Latin America's first priority must be to keep the number of deaths as low as possible.
Politicians must focus on improving healthcare systems, equipping hospitals with resources, temporarily using vacant infrastructure such as hotels or convention centers, and significantly increasing testing capacity.
Moreover, Latin American states must reject export controls on medical supplies and other essential resources and support additional resources for the World Health Organization (WHO) – in stark contrast to US President Donald Trump, who made a reckless decision to freeze approximately 500 million dollars in contributions to the WHO.
We need stronger global cooperation among health authorities to increase testing capacity, treat and isolate patients, and develop treatment options and vaccines – in order to ultimately end the pandemic.
The economic shock is enormous: Not only has Latin American domestic production been interrupted, but the countries there are also suffering from declining export volumes and prices, income losses due to the absence of tourism, fewer remittances from abroad, and significant capital outflows.
The supply shock in large parts of the economy could, together with the decline in demand, trigger a contraction spiral.
To prevent this, bold measures are required to protect household incomes.
This means transferring benefits to the victims of the crisis, including informal and independent workers who have no access to employment subsidies or unemployment insurance.
Reliefs for companies are also important.
Subsidies that help companies pay their wages and wage-related costs protect both them and their employees during the crisis. Thus, they are crucial for a rapid economic recovery after the pandemic.
If the flood of insolvencies is not prevented, the next victims of the pandemic could be the banks.
And at this point, the payment system – and with it the entire economy – is at risk.
Variety of companies, especially small and medium-sized ones, will suffer significant income losses during the crisis.
Without support, the lack of liquidity will soon become a solvency problem.
Tax holidays, payment deferrals and subsidized loans will not be sufficient.
This crisis requires not only unprecedented credit guarantees by governments to ensure that banks continue to lend money, but also temporary regulatory changes to promote credit expansion.
Even well-capitalized and well-managed state banks can play a leading role in this regard.
Allgemeiner betrachtet werden sich die Maßnahmen zwar je nach Land unterscheiden, aber insgesamt werden wohl überall außerordentliche Haushaltsressourcen erforderlich sein, um die Erholung zu beschleunigen.
The governments must stimulate employment and economic activities without exacerbating the dangers to health.
The problem is that the fiscal space in Latin America today is even narrower than after the global financial crisis of 2008.
Therefore, the fiscal burdens must be cushioned by budget adjustments in areas of lower priority.
There is the risk of a downgrade of creditworthiness, which can however be reduced by the governments' promise to correct higher fiscal deficits within an appropriate time frame.
However, external support for budgets and balance of payments is urgently needed – particularly for the small and less developed Latin American countries.
If both private companies and governments run higher deficits, the countries' current account balances are likely to worsen.
The recent capital outflows from emerging countries – one of the largest reversals in the history of modern financial markets – exacerbate the problem further.
The resulting currency devaluations can have a destabilizing effect.
In many economies of the region, the only way to deal with these mutually reinforcing shocks will be to obtain much more external support.
The International Monetary Fund (IMF) plays a crucial role here.
It must take care of the short-term currency and budget needs of countries and continue to support the economies during this crisis, whose duration is highly uncertain.
For this, it needs more resources and the ability to disburse them quickly.
Latin American governments should jointly call for a new version of the IMF's global reserve currency – the Special Drawing Rights (SDRs), which should reach a volume of one trillion SDRs.
Although SDRs are allocated to member countries according to their IMF quotas, a non-proportional allocation could be achieved by establishing a joint pool under the fund's supervision.
Additionally, the IMF could create the necessary capacity through the immediate doubling of the volume of the New Credit Agreements to meet the upcoming strong credit demand.
And finally, the Fund must, since traditional IMF credit programs are not approved in time, improve access to low-cost tools with rapid disbursement – such as its Rapid Financing instrument – or launch new credit facilities for the pandemic.
Major central banks issuing reserve currencies can help by expanding access to currency swaps – either directly or indirectly through the IMF or the Bank for International Settlements, which can channel liquidity to central banks.
Domestically, central banks must use all the instruments available to them and, if necessary, create new ones to supply sufficient liquidity to the financial markets and the economy.
And finally, multilateral development banks (MDBs) such as the World Bank, the Inter-American Development Bank, and the Latin American CAF Development Bank must double the volume of net credit disbursement in the region and tap into highly liquid global capital markets to provide further fiscal support.
Under exceptional circumstances and in countries without market access, official credit disbursement could be supplemented by a debt restructuring.
The MEB should also provide countries with guidelines on the different policy areas involved in crisis management, including their own estimates of COVID-19 infection and mortality rates – particularly for countries where governments downplay the health threat.
Time plays a decisive role in this.
The challenge posed by this pandemic is unprecedented in recent history.
The world and the Latin American and Caribbean region cannot afford delayed or inadequate responses.
G mutual trust, transparency, and reason remain the best guidelines in these uncertain times – and not populism or demagogy.
The crisis must not be used as an excuse to weaken our hard-earned civil rights.
Instead, it can serve as an opportunity to strengthen democracy in Latin America and to show what it can offer its citizens.
